04193nam a22005655i 9780804766265DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20201987cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047662657 a10.1515/97808047662652doi  a(DE-B1597)564735  a(OCoLC)1224278933  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aGN473.4.V56 1987 7aREL0550002bisacsh04a303.6/21 aBurkert, Walter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aViolent Origins :bWalter Burkert, René Girard, and Jonathan Z. Smith on Ritual Killing and Cultural Formation /cJonathan Z. Smith, René Girard, Walter Burkert; Robert G. Hamerton-Kelly. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©1987  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tParticipants -- tIntroduction: Religion and Ritual -- tOne -- tGenerative Scapegoating -- tDiscussion -- tTwo -- tThe Problem of Ritual Killing -- tDiscussion -- tThree -- tThe Domestication of Sacrifice -- tDiscussion -- tFour -- tAnthropological Commentary -- tDiscussion -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBurkert, Girard, and Smith hold important and contradictory theories about the nature and origin of ritual sacrifice, and the role violence plays in religion and culture. These papers and conversations derive from a conference that pursued the possibility and utility of a general theory of religion and culture, especially one based on violence. The special value of this volume is the conversations as such-the real record of working scholars engaged with one another's theories, as they make and meet challenges, and move and maneuver. Girard and Burkert present different versions of the same conviction: that a single theory can account for ritual and its social function, a theory that posits original acts of group violence. Smith sharply questions both the possibility and the utility of such a general theory. Among the highlights of this stimulating interchange of ideas is a searching criticism of Girard's theory of generative scapegoating, which he answers with clarity and conviction, and a challenging of Burkert's theory of the origin of sacrifice in the hunt by Smith's argument, posed as a jeu d'esprit, that sacrifice originates with the domestication of animals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aRELIGION / Christian Rituals & Practice / General.2bisacsh1 aMack, Burton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirard, René, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHamerton-Kelly, Robert G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmith, Jonathan Z., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosaldo, Renato, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirard, René, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurkert, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311070421140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476626540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804766265423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804766265.jpg  a978-3-11-070421-1  SUP eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles